atellofemoral ligament"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Evastus medialis\u003C/strong\u003E is the key dynamic stabiliser of the patellofemoral joint, particularly through its oblique fibres. During knee extension, it provides an essential medial pull on the patella to maintain proper tracking within the femoral groove.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther structures provide additional stability but are not the primary stabilisers:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Emedial patellofemoral ligament\u003C/strong\u003E provides static medial support but is secondary to the dynamic action of vastus medialis\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Elateral retinaculum\u003C/strong\u003E helps prevent excessive medial movement but excessive tightness can contribute to lateral patellar tracking issues.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Equadriceps tendon\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Epatellar tendon\u003C/strong\u003E primarily transmit extensor forces and contribute little to mediolateral stability\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETogether these structures work in concert to maintain proper patellar tracking, with vastus medialis being the most important active stabiliser.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The patellofemoral joint is stabilised by both muscular and bony structures.","The vastus medialis muscle plays a crucial role in maintaining patellar alignment.","The lateral femoral condyle provides a bony restraint to lateral patellar displacement."],"references":["Sud, A., \u0026 Ranjan, R. (2018). Textbook of Orthopaedics, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Singh, V. (2018). Textbook of Anatomy Abdomen and Lower Limb; Volume II (Vol. 2). Elsevier Health Sciences","Cantrell AJ, Imonugo O, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Bony Pelvis